description: Latin praepollens, past participle of praepollere (“to surpass in power”).

entries.meaning: Having superior influence or power; prevailing; predominant.
examples: But the prepollent Gravity of some, being sufficient to give comparative Lightness or Gravity to Bodies, we must deny Nature this Prerogative.

entries.meaning: An extra first digit, or rudiment of a digit, on the preaxial side of the pollex.
